WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
Documents.

00:00:04.700 --> 00:00:06.700
Okay, welcome.

00:00:06.920 --> 00:00:14.380
It's my pleasure to introduce JJ Allaire, who's going to speak to us about publishing Jupyter Notebooks with Quarto.

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:18.959
Thank you. Thanks very much. It's really, really exciting to be here this week.

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:26.379
And I am going to talk about a new scientific and technical publishing system called Quarto that has

00:00:26.860 --> 00:00:28.540
it's based on Jupyter.

00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:33.000
And before I get into all the details of Quarto and how it works with Jupyter,

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.639
I want to talk a little bit about the context of the project, our kind of overall motivation and goals.

00:00:41.099 --> 00:00:48.060
So many of you here have probably read this paper by Brian and Fernando about

00:00:48.619 --> 00:00:53.779
Jupyter and kind of what has made it such an important part of the scientific computing ecosystem.

00:00:53.779 --> 00:00:58.099
And they talk about, certainly interactive computing is a big part of it.

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:03.740
But as you can tell from the title of the paper, a really fundamental part of it is

00:01:04.419 --> 00:01:09.739
Jupyter as a tool for helping you think and tell stories with data, code and data.

00:01:10.419 --> 00:01:14.260
And a big part of using Jupyter is writing.

00:01:14.699 --> 00:01:20.440
And writing, when you're using a Jupyter Notebook, kind of helps you think about what you're going to do.

00:01:20.559 --> 00:01:25.279
By, oftentimes, by writing about the code you're about to execute,

00:01:25.279 --> 00:01:29.519
you maybe think differently about the code and write it a different way. And similarly, when you

00:01:29.959 --> 00:01:37.000
present data or visualizations or metrics in a notebook, writing about it helps the reader

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:40.919
understand the subtleties and context of the data better.

00:01:41.599 --> 00:01:45.919
And many of you may have also seen the Edward Tufte's

00:01:46.720 --> 00:01:53.320
pamphlet, which is sort of a takedown of the reductive style of presenting data with PowerPoint.

00:01:54.040 --> 00:02:01.959
And interesting, I think he'd be quite pleased to hear the previous presentation because one of his big examples in this is about how

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:08.960
NASA approved the ill-fated Space Shuttle launch based on a PowerPoint presentation that was quite reductive,

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:15.399
needed to articulate quite a bit more in terms of narrative and assumptions and subtleties.

00:02:15.639 --> 00:02:21.320
And I think he'd be pretty encouraged to see that that NASA and the JPL is making extensive use of notebooks for

00:02:21.440 --> 00:02:24.960
discussing these kinds of technical things.

00:02:25.759 --> 00:02:27.759
But really,

00:02:28.839 --> 00:02:31.119
metrics and visualizations don't tell the whole story.

00:02:31.679 --> 00:02:36.520
There's assumptions, there's constraints, there's where do we get the data from that are critical.

00:02:36.839 --> 00:02:43.440
And I think this leads to the idea that we need tools to help with telling stories from data.

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:50.720
And it turns out that the scientific community, the scientific tool building community, has been working on

00:02:51.479 --> 00:02:54.960
this for a long time, starting with tech and literate programming,

00:02:55.320 --> 00:03:00.600
through all of the work that has been done on notebooks and various systems, to work on Markdown,

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:03.880
Emacs Org Mode. There's been a lot of work. And I think

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:10.119
in 2023, a lot of that work is really coming together to create the opportunity

00:03:10.440 --> 00:03:16.039
to make a very compelling platform for communicating and telling stories with data.

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:18.479
So that sort of brings me to Quarto.

00:03:19.360 --> 00:03:24.039
What is Quarto? It's a new open-source scientific and technical publishing system.

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:27.559
It builds on standard Markdown, and it's really,

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.960
it's kind of hallmark is it has features that are essential for scientific and technical communication.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:37.399
It is new, but its roots actually go back over 10 years.

00:03:37.399 --> 00:03:41.520
We developed a system called R Markdown that was R-specific.

00:03:42.199 --> 00:03:49.320
That was like about 10 years ago, and we evolved that quite a bit over the years, but really felt pretty bad about the fact that the system

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:55.520
wasn't able to serve the entire scientific computing community. It was just R.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:00.320
And so we actually rewrote it, improved it quite a bit with the lessons learned,

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:05.600
and that was what Quarto represents, which is a sort of multi-language, multi-engine

00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:09.000
re-articulation of the things we did in R Markdown.

00:04:09.880 --> 00:04:14.919
The project is primarily developed and sponsored by Posit. You might not have heard of Posit.

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:19.279
We used to be called RStudio, and we renamed the company Posit to reflect

00:04:19.799 --> 00:04:24.679
the fact that we are doing many of our open-source projects are now multi-language.

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:27.480
Many of our open-source projects are now multi-language.

00:04:28.559 --> 00:04:34.959
The company's sponsored a lot of open-source projects over the years, RStudio itself, Tidyverse, Shiny.

00:04:35.079 --> 00:04:38.079
So Quarto is sort of in that spirit.

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:46.119
And this is a goal that I don't think needs really a lot of emphasis in this audience.

00:04:46.119 --> 00:04:47.640
We all want computational documents.

00:04:47.640 --> 00:04:54.640
I think the one thing we talk about a lot on the Quarto team is to help users fall into a pit of success.

00:04:54.920 --> 00:04:59.279
So we want to make it easier than not to work reproducibly.

00:05:00.200 --> 00:05:03.679
So give people lots of benefits in terms of the type of documents they can produce,

00:05:04.679 --> 00:05:09.359
and then have the entire pipeline of producing documents fundamentally reproducible.

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:15.720
Another goal we talk about is looking at the history of tools for writing

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:19.040
and what some of the benefits and trade-offs are.

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:22.720
If you look at Word, it's a very accessible tool.

00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:25.720
Lots of people open up Word and they know just what to do with it,

00:05:26.079 --> 00:05:29.440
but it actually scales very poorly with document complexity.

00:05:30.119 --> 00:05:34.519
You take a tool like LaTeX, which is considerably harder to use at first,

00:05:34.519 --> 00:05:39.119
but once you learn how to use it, it absorbs complexity very well over time.

00:05:39.239 --> 00:05:42.359
And I think our goal with Quarto is to take Markdown,

00:05:42.359 --> 00:05:45.200
which is a base that's simpler and easier to start with,

00:05:45.559 --> 00:05:48.440
and evolve it to sort of give it the accessibility of Word,

00:05:48.799 --> 00:05:51.959
but also the scalability of systems like LaTeX.

00:05:53.399 --> 00:05:56.119
And then finally, single-source publishing.

00:05:56.119 --> 00:06:00.320
And again, in 2023, when we write content, it's not just,

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:01.959
hey, I wrote a Word doc, here it is.

00:06:01.959 --> 00:06:03.640
It's, I need to publish it on the web.

00:06:04.119 --> 00:06:06.760
I want it to look good on the mobile web.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:09.320
I may need print for scientific publications.

00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:11.160
I might be creating an office document.

00:06:11.519 --> 00:06:14.799
A lot of the content we create today goes into content management systems.

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:20.880
So basically, I want tools that help me publish my analysis and data and notebooks

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:24.519
that support a wide range of output formats.

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:29.519
So I've sort of described the fundamental requirements for these tools

00:06:29.519 --> 00:06:32.839
for computational narratives, being able to interoperate with Jupyter,

00:06:33.160 --> 00:06:36.320
handling technical content, code, citations, cross-refs,

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:38.880
lots of output formats, and extensible.

00:06:39.160 --> 00:06:42.959
Now, there have been tools like this for Jupyter for a long time.

00:06:43.920 --> 00:06:48.359
NbConvert is the obvious one that's been around forever and does all these things.

00:06:48.799 --> 00:06:51.640
But in recent years, there's been some new systems developed,

00:06:51.959 --> 00:06:54.559
JupyterBook, MISTJS, and Quarto.

00:06:55.079 --> 00:06:59.760
And the main, I'd say the main point of departure for these tools is

00:06:59.760 --> 00:07:04.640
that they focus a little more on giving you production quality output out of the box,

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:08.880
but also supporting things like citations and cross-references,

00:07:09.239 --> 00:07:13.079
and then more complex project types like websites, blogs, and books.

00:07:13.480 --> 00:07:17.160
So a lot of these fundamental things have been in NbConvert, NbViewer,

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:21.200
things like that for a long time, but these new tools go quite a bit beyond.

00:07:21.200 --> 00:07:23.279
And so I'm going to talk about Quarto in this talk,

00:07:23.279 --> 00:07:28.119
but I think the other tools are also very much worth a look.

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:30.959
All right, so what are the basics of Quarto?

00:07:30.959 --> 00:07:31.559
How does it work?

00:07:32.119 --> 00:07:36.480
Fundamentally, we start with Jupyter and markdown that's either written

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:38.320
or produced by computations in Jupyter.

00:07:38.799 --> 00:07:42.040
It ends up going into a system called Pandoc, which is a markdown engine,

00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:45.000
which I'll talk a little bit more about a few slides down.

00:07:45.480 --> 00:07:50.880
Pandoc itself is able to produce output in lots and lots of formats,

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:53.799
and that's kind of the basic mechanic of how Quarto works.

00:07:53.799 --> 00:07:59.320
So I'll give you the most straightforward example that you've seen before

00:07:59.320 --> 00:08:00.839
from NbConvert or NbViewer.

00:08:00.839 --> 00:08:02.359
There's nothing really special here.

00:08:02.359 --> 00:08:07.519
It's just taking a notebook that has a table and a plot and producing a webpage from it.

00:08:07.519 --> 00:08:10.559
So again, nothing different or special about that.

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:15.959
But Quarto has lots and lots of options on the order of dozens of options

00:08:15.959 --> 00:08:18.839
that you tailor the output that you produce.

00:08:19.480 --> 00:08:25.279
So as an example, here I've added some options to the kind of front matter of the notebook.

00:08:25.279 --> 00:08:27.839
I want to use a different theme, I want to use a different highlight style,

00:08:27.839 --> 00:08:32.679
and I want to let readers comment on the notebook using hypothesis.

00:08:32.679 --> 00:08:35.960
So when I render this document, you can see the theme is different,

00:08:35.960 --> 00:08:38.880
the highlighting is different, and then you can see this bar on the right

00:08:38.880 --> 00:08:40.320
that provides the ability to comment.

00:08:40.640 --> 00:08:42.559
So that's a document level.

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:44.520
Those are document level options.

00:08:44.520 --> 00:08:47.479
There are also cell level options.

00:08:47.479 --> 00:08:50.479
So here I'm again showing some document level options,

00:08:50.479 --> 00:08:54.119
and these have to do with how code is displayed to the user.

00:08:54.119 --> 00:08:55.599
I'll demo that in a minute.

00:08:55.599 --> 00:08:59.400
But then at the cell level, I'm saying I'd like to provide a caption for my figure,

00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:01.400
I would like it to be a numbered figure,

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:04.479
and I would like to make it cross-referencable by adding these two options

00:09:04.479 --> 00:09:07.119
with this sort of option comment syntax.

00:09:07.119 --> 00:09:11.559
So when I render this, you can see the code is indeed hidden,

00:09:11.559 --> 00:09:17.479
the caption is there and numbered, and the figure is cross-referencable.

00:09:17.479 --> 00:09:21.520
You can see a code menu in the top right, and when I flip that down,

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:24.080
I'm able to show and hide all the code as a reader.

00:09:24.080 --> 00:09:25.599
So those are just examples.

00:09:25.599 --> 00:09:28.520
There's lots and lots of options to let you customize

00:09:28.520 --> 00:09:31.919
kind of the HTML output that you get.

00:09:31.919 --> 00:09:33.080
We mentioned lots of formats.

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:35.719
There's actually dozens of formats available.

00:09:35.719 --> 00:09:38.119
Here's another example of a docx.

00:09:38.119 --> 00:09:40.559
And this is pretty straightforward, just changing the format.

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:45.440
And then I didn't highlight it, but you can see we've got two figures here,

00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:49.359
two plots, and we've specified that we want them laid out in two columns.

00:09:49.359 --> 00:09:55.679
So when we render this, we see the code and then the plots laid out in two columns.

00:09:55.679 --> 00:10:01.799
Another example here is a PDF, and in this case, I'm bringing in a bibliography.

00:10:01.799 --> 00:10:07.719
And it turns out that the optimal reading width is considerably less than 8.5 by 11,

00:10:07.719 --> 00:10:12.000
so a lot of PDFs, that's why you see a lot of two-column output in journals.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.039
So PDFs don't use the full width of the page,

00:10:14.039 --> 00:10:17.000
and web pages don't often use the full width of the page.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.679
So here I'm going to put the citation in the margin,

00:10:19.679 --> 00:10:22.200
and I'm also going to specify that when I show my two figures,

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:26.080
I want it to use beyond the width of the main text.

00:10:26.080 --> 00:10:29.840
So when I render the PDF, you can see that the margin shows up,

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:31.960
the caption shows up in the margin,

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:35.239
and then my plot and code are able to use the full width

00:10:35.239 --> 00:10:37.719
that goes beyond the width of the text.

00:10:37.719 --> 00:10:39.200
These have been documents.

00:10:39.200 --> 00:10:43.159
You can also create presentations with Quarto using Reveal.js.

00:10:43.159 --> 00:10:46.919
This slide deck here was actually created with Quarto.

00:10:46.919 --> 00:10:49.719
And here I'm just saying I want my format to be Reveal.js,

00:10:49.719 --> 00:10:54.000
and I'd like a logo in the bottom right and slide numbers in the top right.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:57.119
And then you can see a slide from that where it shows the figures

00:10:57.119 --> 00:11:00.719
along with the logo and the numbering.

00:11:00.719 --> 00:11:02.880
You notice I didn't show the code here by default.

00:11:02.880 --> 00:11:05.320
When you do a presentation, the code is not shown,

00:11:05.320 --> 00:11:06.960
but you can show the code.

00:11:06.960 --> 00:11:08.640
Here I'm adding a cell option that says,

00:11:08.640 --> 00:11:10.760
please do show the code, because in this example,

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:14.599
I might be trying to teach someone about how to build a plot with Seaborn.

00:11:14.599 --> 00:11:16.799
And I want to highlight specific line numbers

00:11:16.799 --> 00:11:19.960
as I narrate how the plot was constructed.

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:22.719
So here you can see it shows the code and the plot,

00:11:22.719 --> 00:11:24.359
and then this line four is highlighted.

00:11:24.359 --> 00:11:27.359
And when I advance the slide, then line five will be highlighted.

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:30.239
So this is a good way of explaining code

00:11:30.239 --> 00:11:34.719
or explaining how things are done using a slide.

00:11:34.719 --> 00:11:37.799
I've sort of focused mostly on individual documents,

00:11:37.799 --> 00:11:41.799
but Quarto has a project system that lets you aggregate lots of documents

00:11:41.799 --> 00:11:43.359
together.

00:11:43.359 --> 00:11:47.960
This is a simple Quarto project file that says,

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:52.000
I want to build a website, some options for the website

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.119
and how navigation works on the website,

00:11:54.119 --> 00:11:57.000
and then some options that are shared options for all

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.320
of the HTML documents in the website.

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:02.200
So that's the basic mechanic of a simple project.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:05.000
In the real world, there's more configuration that goes on.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.760
Here's an example of the website for the Fast AI Deep Learning

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:10.799
for Coders course.

00:12:10.799 --> 00:12:14.320
And here you can see there's a bit of social options related

00:12:14.320 --> 00:12:16.880
to social sharing, options related to links back

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:20.719
to the repo that was used to produce the website,

00:12:20.719 --> 00:12:22.799
customizing the navigation.

00:12:22.799 --> 00:12:24.960
And you can see here, this is now a website

00:12:24.960 --> 00:12:26.719
where all of these documents on the left

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:29.119
are separate documents that are all brought together

00:12:29.119 --> 00:12:31.799
with navigation into a website.

00:12:31.799 --> 00:12:33.840
So that's a website.

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:35.159
Blogs are a little bit different.

00:12:35.159 --> 00:12:37.559
The navigation for blogs is different.

00:12:37.559 --> 00:12:39.840
And so we have some features that support that.

00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:42.640
Here you can see similar, some get oriented options,

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:46.280
some social sharing oriented options, some navigation options.

00:12:46.280 --> 00:12:48.919
And here the home page provides like a tiled display

00:12:48.919 --> 00:12:50.679
of posts and categories.

00:12:50.679 --> 00:12:53.960
So that's another type of aggregate project

00:12:53.960 --> 00:12:54.760
that you might see.

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:57.080
And then books are another one, where here I'm

00:12:57.080 --> 00:12:58.919
showing I've got a cover image, I've

00:12:58.919 --> 00:13:01.159
got an explicit list of chapters.

00:13:01.159 --> 00:13:02.559
And when the book is rendered, you

00:13:02.559 --> 00:13:04.159
can see the chapters are numbered,

00:13:04.159 --> 00:13:06.400
the subsections are numbered.

00:13:06.400 --> 00:13:08.520
Cross-references go across chapters

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:11.359
and use the section numbering.

00:13:11.359 --> 00:13:13.440
So books, again, slightly different than websites.

00:13:13.440 --> 00:13:15.119
They are a website, but they actually

00:13:15.119 --> 00:13:17.760
have more structure built into them.

00:13:17.760 --> 00:13:20.559
This is a web version of a book.

00:13:20.559 --> 00:13:22.119
But when you write a book with Quarto,

00:13:22.119 --> 00:13:24.479
it actually supports, there's five different formats.

00:13:24.479 --> 00:13:26.200
So it's very useful to have a web version,

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:29.840
but you often want to print version, perhaps a Word

00:13:29.840 --> 00:13:32.679
version for mobile readers, an EPUB version.

00:13:32.679 --> 00:13:36.640
And then ASCIDoc is actually useful for publishing.

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:38.400
Manning and O'Reilly both use ASCIDoc

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:42.039
as their kind of fundamental sort of underlying format

00:13:42.039 --> 00:13:44.440
for publishing books.

00:13:44.440 --> 00:13:48.239
OK, so I've covered some of the basics of output formats,

00:13:48.239 --> 00:13:49.780
some of the obvious output formats

00:13:49.799 --> 00:13:51.580
that you'd expect to see.

00:13:51.580 --> 00:13:53.380
But Quarto was built on, as I said,

00:13:53.380 --> 00:13:56.659
Pandoc, which has been around for quite a long time.

00:13:56.659 --> 00:13:58.979
It's almost 20 years.

00:13:58.979 --> 00:14:00.580
It was created by John McFarlane, who's

00:14:00.580 --> 00:14:02.700
a philosophy professor at Berkeley.

00:14:02.700 --> 00:14:05.419
He's also been very, very active in the standards

00:14:05.419 --> 00:14:06.739
community around Markdown.

00:14:06.739 --> 00:14:10.219
He was the main author of the Common Mark spec and reference

00:14:10.219 --> 00:14:11.380
implementations.

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:13.140
So Pandoc you can think of as Common Mark,

00:14:13.140 --> 00:14:16.020
plus many extensions for technical writing,

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:18.739
citations being the foremost of those.

00:14:18.739 --> 00:14:22.179
But there are lots of other extensions.

00:14:22.179 --> 00:14:24.700
And Pandoc, the reason we love Pandoc so much

00:14:24.700 --> 00:14:28.859
as a foundation, it supports dozens of output formats.

00:14:28.859 --> 00:14:30.719
That system is extensible.

00:14:30.719 --> 00:14:32.940
You can create custom writers for new formats.

00:14:32.940 --> 00:14:37.020
You can do lots of filtering of documents.

00:14:37.020 --> 00:14:40.219
So it's a great foundation for building a publishing system.

00:14:40.219 --> 00:14:42.580
And as you can see, I mentioned the obvious things

00:14:42.580 --> 00:14:43.859
like HTML, PDF, and Word.

00:14:43.859 --> 00:14:47.739
But it also supports OpenOffice, different presentation types,

00:14:47.739 --> 00:14:49.219
lots of different Markdown flavors,

00:14:49.219 --> 00:14:53.219
which becomes important in content management systems,

00:14:53.219 --> 00:14:56.179
wikis, some other formats you may or may not

00:14:56.179 --> 00:14:58.340
have been exposed to, but which are quite important

00:14:58.340 --> 00:15:00.580
in various communities.

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:02.419
So it's a really, really powerful and flexible

00:15:02.419 --> 00:15:06.460
foundation for creating lots of different types of output.

00:15:06.460 --> 00:15:07.780
And we've used that.

00:15:07.780 --> 00:15:10.380
We've created some custom formats for popular content

00:15:10.380 --> 00:15:11.859
management systems.

00:15:11.859 --> 00:15:14.780
So Hugo, you may have heard of, it's for building websites.

00:15:14.780 --> 00:15:17.020
They use their own flavor of Markdown

00:15:17.020 --> 00:15:18.780
called Goldmark Markdown.

00:15:18.780 --> 00:15:21.380
We're able to produce Goldmark Markdown from Cordo.

00:15:21.380 --> 00:15:25.580
Docasaurus uses another system for documentation publishing,

00:15:25.580 --> 00:15:28.179
uses MDX Markdown, a whole different flavor.

00:15:28.179 --> 00:15:30.659
Confluence uses, actually not Markdown at all,

00:15:30.659 --> 00:15:32.539
but a custom XML format.

00:15:32.539 --> 00:15:34.500
And then O'Reilly uses ASCIDoc.

00:15:34.500 --> 00:15:36.979
So we can take that same notebook

00:15:36.979 --> 00:15:39.380
that we started off at the beginning, and in this case,

00:15:39.380 --> 00:15:42.099
we're going to produce from the notebook Goldmark Markdown.

00:15:42.099 --> 00:15:45.219
And now that notebook's available inside a Hugo website

00:15:45.219 --> 00:15:46.900
here as a blog post.

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:49.859
Similarly, with Docasaurus, we have the same notebook.

00:15:49.859 --> 00:15:52.419
And we tell Cordo to render MDX Markdown.

00:15:52.419 --> 00:15:55.340
And then we can see that notebook inside our Docasaurus

00:15:55.340 --> 00:15:57.099
site.

00:15:57.099 --> 00:15:59.700
Confluence, similarly, same notebook.

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:02.979
Confluence XML is sort of HTML plus plus plus.

00:16:02.979 --> 00:16:06.219
There's lots of particularities of it.

00:16:06.219 --> 00:16:08.260
But we were able to create a custom writer

00:16:08.260 --> 00:16:10.700
so that then your notebook also shows up

00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:12.380
inside a Confluence site.

00:16:12.380 --> 00:16:15.140
And then finally, I referenced O'Reilly.

00:16:15.140 --> 00:16:16.780
We have a bunch of people writing books,

00:16:16.780 --> 00:16:18.419
O'Reilly books with Cordo.

00:16:18.419 --> 00:16:21.460
You produce the ASCIDoc to O'Reilly spec.

00:16:21.460 --> 00:16:23.580
And then they can use that to create their own print,

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:26.500
EPUB, and web versions of the book.

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:28.700
So using Pandoc as a foundation lets

00:16:28.700 --> 00:16:31.140
us target this huge range of output formats

00:16:31.140 --> 00:16:33.059
and lets you even create your own writers

00:16:33.059 --> 00:16:35.500
to target new formats.

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:37.539
Another exciting initiative that we have,

00:16:37.539 --> 00:16:40.059
we're actually working with people in the open science

00:16:40.059 --> 00:16:41.859
community, some scientific publishers,

00:16:41.859 --> 00:16:44.859
as well as the folks who are behind JupyterBook

00:16:45.059 --> 00:16:47.940
and Mist.js to kind of create a standard for including notebooks

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:50.260
in scientific publications.

00:16:50.260 --> 00:16:53.380
And we're really excited about that.

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:55.419
So there'll be more details on that probably

00:16:55.419 --> 00:16:59.739
in the next couple of months, so keep an eye out for that.

00:16:59.739 --> 00:17:03.419
So the basic workflow of Cordo, kind of how you use it.

00:17:03.419 --> 00:17:05.099
There are two main, I would say, verbs.

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:09.619
One is render, saying take a notebook and create a document.

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:12.420
Here you can see just render the notebook to the default format.

00:17:12.420 --> 00:17:16.819
Here we can see render the notebook to docx.

00:17:16.819 --> 00:17:18.420
And then the other big verb is preview,

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:20.099
which is render the notebook, but then give me

00:17:20.099 --> 00:17:21.020
a live preview of it.

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:24.099
So as I save it and update it, update the preview

00:17:24.099 --> 00:17:26.020
so I see what it looks like.

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:27.900
And then I'll talk a little bit about this.

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:29.420
There's another sort of variation

00:17:29.420 --> 00:17:31.979
of notebooks that's plain text that you can also use.

00:17:31.979 --> 00:17:33.579
I'll describe that in a minute.

00:17:33.579 --> 00:17:37.180
So here's a basic workflow where you have a Jupyter notebook

00:17:37.180 --> 00:17:38.819
running locally.

00:17:38.819 --> 00:17:41.060
And side by side, the web page that's actually

00:17:41.060 --> 00:17:45.420
produced from the notebook, as you run cells and save,

00:17:45.420 --> 00:17:49.140
the preview automatically updates.

00:17:49.140 --> 00:17:50.660
I talked about plain text notebooks.

00:17:50.660 --> 00:17:54.099
And actually, there's quite a few different formats

00:17:54.099 --> 00:17:55.420
for plain text notebooks.

00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:56.900
There's a project called Jupytext,

00:17:56.900 --> 00:17:59.579
which translates between IPy and B and plain text formats.

00:17:59.579 --> 00:18:01.979
And there are actually 10 different formats,

00:18:01.979 --> 00:18:06.979
five .py scripts formats and five markdown-based formats

00:18:06.979 --> 00:18:08.660
for representing notebooks in plain text.

00:18:08.660 --> 00:18:10.859
And representing notebooks in plain text

00:18:10.859 --> 00:18:13.380
can be, for some situations, useful

00:18:13.380 --> 00:18:16.140
because you can use any standard text editor.

00:18:16.140 --> 00:18:18.579
Works well with version control, although there's

00:18:18.579 --> 00:18:20.099
quite a bit of innovation, as we saw,

00:18:20.099 --> 00:18:22.780
going on in using notebooks in version control.

00:18:22.780 --> 00:18:25.579
But here you can see I've got the options in front matter.

00:18:25.579 --> 00:18:27.219
I've got a code cell.

00:18:27.219 --> 00:18:30.619
I've got markdown, another code cell, and then

00:18:30.619 --> 00:18:32.020
options inside the code cell.

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:33.099
So that's another option.

00:18:33.099 --> 00:18:36.579
And if you're using plain text notebooks,

00:18:36.579 --> 00:18:40.079
there's a VS Code extension that lets you provide lots of tools

00:18:40.119 --> 00:18:42.839
for editing them and also lets you do the sort of things

00:18:42.839 --> 00:18:45.000
you might do in a normal notebook,

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.319
like running cells and running lines of code.

00:18:47.319 --> 00:18:49.280
So that is an option.

00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:51.880
And again, it's sort of different tasks and tools

00:18:51.880 --> 00:18:54.199
are called for for different projects.

00:18:54.199 --> 00:18:56.839
You have the option, of course, to use IPy and B or QMD.

00:18:56.839 --> 00:18:58.719
And we also have a JupyterLab extension

00:18:58.719 --> 00:19:01.239
that helps out with authoring for IPy and B.

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:05.680
And that rendering pipeline, I showed this before.

00:19:05.680 --> 00:19:07.239
For notebooks, we're not going to execute

00:19:07.239 --> 00:19:09.520
the notebook by default, so we assume that execution

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:11.839
is done inside JupyterLab.

00:19:11.839 --> 00:19:13.359
But you can re-execute everything

00:19:13.359 --> 00:19:17.040
if you want for reproducibility or to reflect updated data.

00:19:17.040 --> 00:19:19.319
And then the plain text workflow takes the QMD,

00:19:19.319 --> 00:19:22.719
turns it into a Jupyter notebook, executes it,

00:19:22.719 --> 00:19:24.079
and so on.

00:19:24.079 --> 00:19:25.520
Same sort of process.

00:19:25.520 --> 00:19:28.119
There are some tools that are available for caching,

00:19:28.119 --> 00:19:31.359
because if you're re-executing the notebook every time,

00:19:31.359 --> 00:19:35.880
that could be time consuming in a way that's undesirable.

00:19:35.880 --> 00:19:38.160
So we have integration with JupyterCache

00:19:38.199 --> 00:19:40.560
from the executable books project,

00:19:40.560 --> 00:19:42.400
as well as an internal caching system

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:44.040
we have in Cordo called Freeze.

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:47.520
So again, I'm not going to try to plumb the depths

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:49.040
of how all the trade-offs here,

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:51.680
but there's lots of options for kind of how you work,

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:55.459
how you cache things, plain text versus notebooks, et cetera.

00:19:57.199 --> 00:20:00.520
There are quite a few ways to extend Cordo.

00:20:00.520 --> 00:20:03.560
We have an extension system that encompasses

00:20:03.560 --> 00:20:05.680
filters and shortcodes, which are sort of like

00:20:05.680 --> 00:20:07.959
creating sort of new markdown syntax

00:20:07.959 --> 00:20:10.400
and macros for generating content.

00:20:10.400 --> 00:20:11.880
You can write your own formats.

00:20:11.880 --> 00:20:13.959
Lots of people have written formats for,

00:20:13.959 --> 00:20:16.839
there's probably 15 or 20 formats for academic journals

00:20:16.839 --> 00:20:18.479
to produce the LaTeX that's required

00:20:18.479 --> 00:20:20.280
for various academic journals.

00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:23.280
And then some things for creating custom project types.

00:20:23.280 --> 00:20:25.599
I'll talk just briefly about filters.

00:20:25.599 --> 00:20:28.300
And the idea behind a filter is that it transforms

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:30.520
the document before final rendering.

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:32.760
You can implement lots and lots of things with filters.

00:20:33.479 --> 00:20:37.000
Again, content generation, content filtering,

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.540
doing format-specific things.

00:20:39.540 --> 00:20:40.839
I'll give an example of a filter

00:20:40.839 --> 00:20:42.640
using the PanFlute library.

00:20:42.640 --> 00:20:45.260
Here you can see I'm rendering a notebook,

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:47.319
and I'm saying, please run this filter

00:20:47.319 --> 00:20:48.880
when the notebook is rendered.

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:51.239
This is the whole source code for the filter.

00:20:51.239 --> 00:20:53.359
Most of it's just scaffolding the real,

00:20:53.359 --> 00:20:55.959
this is a really trivially simple filter,

00:20:55.959 --> 00:20:57.880
which basically says if there's a header,

00:20:57.880 --> 00:20:59.520
then bump the header up by one.

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:02.839
So if there's a H3, make it an H,

00:21:02.839 --> 00:21:04.040
or if there's a, sorry, if there's an H2,

00:21:04.040 --> 00:21:05.599
make it an H3, and so on.

00:21:05.599 --> 00:21:08.359
Really simple, but it turns out that filters

00:21:08.359 --> 00:21:12.920
can do a lot of things, and many of the features

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:15.319
in Quarto are implemented as filters.

00:21:15.319 --> 00:21:18.680
So cross-reference and citations, embedded languages,

00:21:18.680 --> 00:21:21.800
macro substitution, image conversion.

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:24.339
And so we actually have dozens of filters built into Quarto,

00:21:24.339 --> 00:21:26.359
but you can actually write your own filters.

00:21:26.359 --> 00:21:29.119
So many times, users who want a feature

00:21:29.680 --> 00:21:31.079
do not need to wait for us to implement the feature.

00:21:31.079 --> 00:21:33.839
You can just implement shortcodes and filters

00:21:33.839 --> 00:21:35.800
to get the functionality you want.

00:21:35.800 --> 00:21:37.959
There's dozens of them you can find on our site,

00:21:37.959 --> 00:21:39.800
but here's some examples.

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:42.439
Lightbox treatments for images in HTML,

00:21:42.439 --> 00:21:47.119
a shortcode for embedding chemistry visualizations,

00:21:47.119 --> 00:21:51.920
QR codes, more tailored options for how code is displayed.

00:21:51.920 --> 00:21:54.079
So filters are a really, really powerful way

00:21:54.079 --> 00:21:56.119
to extend the system.

00:21:56.119 --> 00:21:58.560
There's a couple ways to write filters in Python.

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:02.199
Pandoc filters, which was from the creator of Pandoc,

00:22:02.199 --> 00:22:04.319
and then Panflute, which is what I just showed.

00:22:04.319 --> 00:22:06.280
It's a little more modern.

00:22:06.280 --> 00:22:09.880
Lua filters, there's an embedded Lua interpreter in Pandoc

00:22:09.880 --> 00:22:11.359
which you can use for zero dependencies,

00:22:11.359 --> 00:22:14.359
and you can also write them in any language with JSON.

00:22:15.359 --> 00:22:18.040
Finally, I just was now talking about

00:22:18.040 --> 00:22:19.680
how to extend Quarto from within.

00:22:19.680 --> 00:22:22.280
You can also embed Quarto in other workflows.

00:22:22.280 --> 00:22:24.359
I believe later today, Hamill's gonna give a talk

00:22:24.359 --> 00:22:26.880
about NBDev, which is a system for developing

00:22:26.880 --> 00:22:30.160
Python packages entirely in Jupyter Notebooks,

00:22:30.160 --> 00:22:32.199
and NBDev version two uses Quarto

00:22:32.199 --> 00:22:37.199
to produce documentation websites from NBDev projects.

00:22:38.199 --> 00:22:40.479
So lots of ways, since it's a command line tool,

00:22:40.479 --> 00:22:43.000
to embed it in other workflows and customize it.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:45.359
So that's all I have.

00:22:46.280 --> 00:22:47.880
Would love to take questions.

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:51.079
We have a, Posit has a booth just out here,

00:22:51.079 --> 00:22:53.839
so if we don't get to your questions now,

00:22:53.839 --> 00:22:54.800
just come by, I'll be there,

00:22:54.800 --> 00:22:55.959
and the rest of us will be there.

00:22:55.959 --> 00:22:58.439
We'll happen to answer questions this afternoon.

00:22:59.359 --> 00:23:00.719
Thank you.

00:23:00.719 --> 00:23:01.560
Thank you.

00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:02.400
Thank you.

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:03.239
Thank you.

00:23:03.239 --> 00:23:04.060
Thank you.

00:23:04.060 --> 00:23:05.400
Thank you.

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:07.560
Okay, are there any questions?

00:23:07.560 --> 00:23:08.400
Yes.

00:23:15.359 --> 00:23:17.439
Thank you very much for the presentation.

00:23:17.439 --> 00:23:19.040
I have two questions.

00:23:19.040 --> 00:23:22.040
The first question is, is it possible

00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:26.920
to have some interactivity in the Quattro?

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:30.280
So can I, for example, interact with data

00:23:30.280 --> 00:23:33.839
and re-render the website, something like that.

00:23:33.839 --> 00:23:37.359
The second question, is it possible to use Quattro

00:23:37.359 --> 00:23:40.719
as a rendering engine on GitHub?

00:23:40.719 --> 00:23:44.520
So for example, I have repository of notebooks

00:23:44.520 --> 00:23:46.719
and I opened the notebook in the GitHub,

00:23:46.719 --> 00:23:51.479
so I would like to see the output from the Quattro.

00:23:51.479 --> 00:23:53.160
Is it possible to use it?

00:23:53.160 --> 00:23:55.359
Okay, so on interactivity,

00:23:55.359 --> 00:23:57.000
there's a bunch of different ways to interactivity.

00:23:57.000 --> 00:23:59.319
You can use Jupyter widgets.

00:23:59.319 --> 00:24:02.760
You can use observable JavaScript.

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:07.760
You can also using, you can use Pyedide and Wasm

00:24:08.239 --> 00:24:12.119
to embed interactive Python applications

00:24:12.119 --> 00:24:13.160
inside Quattro documents.

00:24:13.160 --> 00:24:15.880
So Quattro is, you know, it's deployed

00:24:15.880 --> 00:24:18.920
as a client-side asset.

00:24:18.920 --> 00:24:21.119
So the interactivity is gonna be all in JavaScript

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:22.719
and we're using Wasm and Pyedide,

00:24:22.719 --> 00:24:25.040
but there are lots of different ways to do that.

00:24:25.040 --> 00:24:26.520
And they're outlined on there.

00:24:26.520 --> 00:24:28.760
We have a whole section about interactivity

00:24:28.760 --> 00:24:30.119
that talks about all the different options

00:24:30.119 --> 00:24:31.800
and how they work.

00:24:31.800 --> 00:24:34.040
And then on GitHub, we have support for,

00:24:34.040 --> 00:24:35.439
we have a Quattro publish command

00:24:35.439 --> 00:24:37.199
that supports GitHub pages.

00:24:37.199 --> 00:24:40.000
So it's very easy to say I have notebooks in a repository

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:41.520
and I want them to be published.

00:24:41.520 --> 00:24:44.040
The GitHub viewer is controlled by GitHub.

00:24:44.040 --> 00:24:46.400
So I, we're not able to,

00:24:46.400 --> 00:24:47.959
and maybe there's an extension API

00:24:47.959 --> 00:24:51.400
that we could use to override the default display,

00:24:51.400 --> 00:24:54.880
but that is something that I don't know if is hookable,

00:24:54.880 --> 00:24:56.959
but again, you can have,

00:24:56.959 --> 00:25:00.119
GitHub can host the published notebooks using GitHub pages.

00:25:02.160 --> 00:25:04.239
Hey, any more questions?

00:25:04.239 --> 00:25:05.079
Yes.

00:25:18.760 --> 00:25:19.800
Thank you.

00:25:19.800 --> 00:25:21.359
Thanks for the nice talk.

00:25:22.800 --> 00:25:26.599
Is Quattro going to replace some of the R packages

00:25:26.599 --> 00:25:28.400
like block down and book down?

00:25:28.400 --> 00:25:29.239
Yes, yes.

00:25:29.239 --> 00:25:31.520
So Quattro is kind of the next generation.

00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:34.239
We built a lot of things in within R Markdown

00:25:34.239 --> 00:25:36.880
for things like books and blogs and websites.

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:39.560
And this is sort of our re-imagining of all that

00:25:39.560 --> 00:25:43.160
that works with R and Python and Julia.

00:25:43.160 --> 00:25:46.040
So it really is a replacement for those things.

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:49.079
And the future evolution of all those capabilities

00:25:49.079 --> 00:25:51.599
are going to be in Quattro, not in those packages.

00:25:54.160 --> 00:25:55.239
More questions?

00:25:57.239 --> 00:25:59.920
We have time for another question if there is one.

00:26:03.359 --> 00:26:04.199
Okay.

00:26:04.199 --> 00:26:05.040
Thank you very much, Jason.

00:26:05.040 --> 00:26:05.880
Thank you.

00:26:06.079 --> 00:26:06.920
Thank you.

00:26:06.920 --> 00:26:07.760
Thank you.

